                    "@type": "Question",
                    "name": "What should I invest my money with?",
                    "acceptedAnswer": {
                        "@type": "Answer",
                        "text": "There are several different types of investment accounts to get started with. If you prefer a hands-off approach, you can open an account with a robo-advisor that will create an appropriate portfolio for you automatically. You can open a standard brokerage account to invests in stocks, bonds, mutual funds, and ETFs. Or, you can open a retirement account like an IRA to invest in those things, which could give you some big tax advantages.",
                        "author": {
                            "@type": "Organization",
                            "name": "The Motley Fool"
                        }
                    }
                },
                {
                    "@type": "Question",
                    "name": "What is good to invest in with $100?",
                    "acceptedAnswer": {
                        "@type": "Answer",
                        "text": "If you&amp;#x27;re starting with $100 or a similar amount of money, there are some good choices for you. You could use a robo-advisor to start an automated investment account and add to it periodically. You can open a brokerage account and invest in an index fund. And with more brokers offering fractional share investing, you can even create a portfolio of individual stocks with a $100 initial investment.",
                        "author": {
                            "@type": "Organization",
                            "name": "The Motley Fool"
                        }
                    }
                },
                {
                    "@type": "Question",
                    "name": "What is the No. 1 thing to invest in?",
                    "acceptedAnswer": {
                        "@type": "Answer",
                        "text": "This depends on your particular goals, risk tolerance, and available capital. For example, there&amp;#x27;s a solid argument to be made that buying simple S&amp;amp;P 500 index funds is the best investment for most people, but there&amp;#x27;s also an argument to be made in favor of individual stocks for investors with the time and desire to research their investment choices.",
                        "author": {
                            "@type": "Organization",
                            "name": "The Motley Fool"
                        }
                    }
                }
